 Its reasons are as follows: From my self-introduction the only explicit preference is that I "enjoy listening to CDs very much." Because no specific genre likes or dislikes are stated, I evaluate the two candidates by what a CD enthusiast typically values: production quality, album sequencing/cohesion, historical significance, and an immersive listening experience that benefits from the CD format.
Abbey Road (Rock; Progressive; Progressive Rock) is a classic, album-length work by The Beatles noted for its exemplary studio production, inventive arrangements, and the famous side-two medley that creates a continuous, carefully sequenced listening experience. It contains widely recognized, high-quality tracks such as "Come Together," "Something," and "Here Comes the Sun," and its studio techniques (advanced production under George Martin, creative use of studio instruments and effects including early Moog use, and meticulous mixing) make it particularly rewarding when listened to on CD. Those attributes — cohesive sequencing, sonic detail, and historical/artistic significance — align directly with what a CD enthusiast who enjoys deep, attentive listening would appreciate.
I reject I Will Always Love You: The Best Of Whitney Houston not because it lacks merit — it showcases Whitney Houston’s extraordinary vocal performances and contains major hits like "I Will Always Love You" — but because it is a compilation of singles rather than a single, cohesive album experience. As a CD listener focused on immersive albums and studio craftsmanship, a greatest-hits compilation tends to prioritize individual-track highlights over the continuous sequencing and studio-driven narrative that make a classic studio album like Abbey Road especially satisfying on CD. Therefore, Abbey Road better aligns with the listening priorities implied by my enjoyment of CDs.

